    <h1>Monads</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">Bartosz Milewski · 2016-2017 · <a href="https://bartoszmilewski.com/2016/11/21/monads-programmers-definition/">Category Theory for Programmers, Ch. 17</a></p>

    <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mb-6">Prereqs: <a href="/reading/category-theory/milewski-04/">🍞 Ch4 (Kleisli Categories)</a>, <a href="/reading/category-theory/milewski-07/">🍞 Ch7 (Functors)</a>, <a href="/reading/category-theory/milewski-10/">🍞 Ch10 (Natural Transformations)</a>. 12 min.</p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none">A monad is a functor <strong>M</strong> equipped with two natural transformations: <code>return</code> (&eta; : a &rarr; M(a)) and <code>join</code> (&mu; : M(M(a)) &rarr; M(a)). Equivalently, <code>bind</code> (&gt;&gt;=) replaces both. The monad laws (associativity, left/right identity) are the Kleisli category's composition laws. Monads compose effects: partiality, nondeterminism, logging, state.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- 1. Return and join -->
    <h3>Return and join: the categorical definition</h3>
    <p>A monad on a category C is an endofunctor M : C &rarr; C with two natural transformations: <strong>return</strong> (&eta; : Id &rarr; M) embeds a pure value, and <strong>join</strong> (&mu; : M&#8728;M &rarr; M) collapses a nested layer. The monad laws: join is associative, return is its two-sided identity. This is a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monad_(category_theory)"><img src="/reading/wikipedia.svg" alt="wp" style="display:inline;height:1em;vertical-align:-0.1em;margin-right:0.2em;"/>monoid in the category of endofunctors</a>.</p>

    <!-- SVG: Monad operations — return and join -->
